    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.35c.11"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">11</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="italics">Evert Bergstrom
                        <lb/>
                    2249 Kenilworth Avenue 
                        <lb/>
                    Los Angeles, California 90039</hi> 
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>October 23, 1971</dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I take the liberty of writing you again re-peating the request I made in my letter of last May in which I asked for an opportunity to see you prior and preparatory to my attempt to write an appreciative essay of you. In reply to my letter your daughter stated that you would grant me an interview and suggested that a date be set.</p>
                
                <p>However, by the time your daughter's letter arrived (at my home) I was in Europe, and my wife did send it to me. I knew then that I would be in Europe some months and in my letter to your daughter I suggested that the matter of fixing a date should await my return to <hi rend="caps">U.S.A.</hi></p> 
                
                <p>You may receive two copies of this letter that and the fact that I am addressing you instead of your <add>^daughter</add> calls for an explanation: Before leaving Sweden I discarded all the letters I had received from the family. In so doing, I also discarded the letter from your daughter, inadvertently, of course. So now I don't have your daughters<sic>daughter's</sic> name or address. Therefore, I am sending one copy 
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.35b.12"/>
                
                <fw type="authorial"><hi rend="underline">2</hi></fw>
                <fw type="curatorial">12</fw>
                
                    via Dick Cavett, <hi rend="caps">A.B.C.</hi> New York and another via your publisher &#8212; University of Nebraska Press, thus increasing my chances to reach you.</p> 
                
                <p>Under the circumstances, I trust you will not take offense, should you receive both letters and I also hope your daughter will understand why this letter is addressed to you and not to her.</p> 
                
                <p>If the invitation to see you still stand, I will appear as when and where it suits your convenience.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Evert Bergstrom</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
